<p>
    A historic moment in this nations history, a first of it's kind ever to be done. The Seminole Nation of Oklahoma became the first in the country to ban any data center construction on it's land. This being a unanimous 24 - 0 vote. NDA's or Non Disclose Agreements are a common thing that Technology Companies use. They are used in a manner that typically circumvents any public discussion or recourse, and have been used in ever more increasingly alarming rate to force open data center construction on smaller communities. It is going to be discussed heavily in these topics. In specific to The Great Seminole Nation of Oklahoma, they were approached by a tech company with NDA's with the intent on constructing a Data Center on their land. After which they voted to never allow any data centers on their land in the coming future.
</p>


<p id="topicTwoMore" style="display: none;">

    Nation wide, this is becoming increasingly more common. This article in specific references a Two Bulls' Democracy Now! interview, in where she mentions that there are around 103 to 160 proposed hyper scale data centers, that being even larger then regular data centers. A tactic that she names is called the bait-and-switch. It terms the actions of tech companies getting smaller communities to sign NDA's, with the promises of investments on renewable energy and infrastructure. Then when signed, they are forced to go along with a hyper scale data center. Getting essentially blackmailed on the terms of breaking the NDA and getting sued. It is a malicious tactic that is just incomprehensibly evil. They target these smaller Indigenous Communities because of their access to resources. The same resources they already exploit, they are simply looking for a cheaper alternative to paying what they rightfully owe. Because of the poverty most of these communities face, they are chosen to exploit for cheaper labor, cheaper workers, and when it is all built, they are then used for cheap waste disposal as well. Simply being forced into a colonial cycle that has been ever persuasive for centuries now. A quote that struck me very hard was said by Ash Leitka, in which she states "Communities want clean water, privacy and security, jobs and economic stability .... and hyper scale date centers threaten every negatively impact every single one of those points.", She also calls the AI infrastructure boom a "A falsely generated demand", which is going to be in a "death cycle". All quotes that shows a deeper understanding of this colonial cycle that continues on, just in different forms. The death cycle being literal in the sense of where, a data center pops up, essentially draining and killing the region, leaving it a waste. 
</p>
